title: Video GPT by Veed: Epic fail!  #fail #AINotSoIntelligent #WhatAreYouDoing
content:
I've been using this service for a couple of weeks now. Initially, I thought it was amazing, but my experience changed when I started using it to create videos through "Video GPT by Veed."

I gave very specific instructions, such as: "Please create a YouTube Shorts video about 10 inventions that were made by accident. Here is an itemized, numbered list of the inventions to include. The video should be between 45 and 57 seconds long (as YouTube Shorts cannot exceed 60 seconds). Additionally, generate an engaging video title with five top hashtags. I need a video description with 15 of the best hashtags (since YouTube penalizes creators for exceeding 15 hashtags due to their community guidelines). Also, include tags that are no more than 500 characters (the maximum allowed by YouTube) but no less than 499 characters."

Despite these detailed instructions, the videos produced were very general and did not specifically discuss the inventions I listed or mention when they were invented. After several unsuccessful attempts to get the desired output, I received a message saying, "You've reached your limit for using GPTs. Upgrade to ChatGPT Plus or try again after 7:30 A.M."

This was frustrating. The tool couldn't meet my needs, yet it was prompting me to upgrade to a paid service. It feels like ChatGPT is intentionally designed to frustrate users into paying for its monthly service. If this is the case, I can assure you that I will never spend a penny on it!

title: Brain dead
content:
ChatGPT is literally brain dead, and here‚Äôs why: 
1: I use it for roleplaying sometimes, but it‚Äôs often inconsistent and doesn‚Äôt follow paths clearly. 
I ask it to roleplay certain characters and it either drifts off topic, acts as my character instead, or literally says it can‚Äôt continue after literally an hour of roleplaying. 
2: Not only that, but it doesn‚Äôt follow clear instructions. I give it a command and it eventually does the opposite. When I ask it to do something differently, it rephrases or barely changes the way it first did it wrong.
3: It gives misinformation as well. I ask it to describe characters and it miscolors them, alters their character, or misses parts. The entire reason this app was made is FOR information.
Overall, depending on the way you use it, it can be good, but this is incredibly disappointing for what it should be. It gives misleading information and it doesn‚Äôt follow directions even when clear. Please fix these issues. Thank you.

title: Urgent: Critical Issues with ChatGPT‚Äôs Functionality ‚Äì Immediate Fix Required‚Äù
content:
I have been using this app for months and paying the $20 subscription, but my experience has been incredibly frustrating. The app consistently fails to follow simple instructions. It often does the complete opposite of what I ask, despite my instructions being very clear and straightforward.

When I request an illustration, the app should be able to follow a simple outline accurately. Instead, I have to ask multiple times, and it still doesn‚Äôt listen. To make matters worse, I often receive notifications saying I‚Äôve used up my image limit. This is unacceptable.

In today‚Äôs world, there‚Äôs no excuse for poor technology. When I request a redo of an illustration, the app should modify the existing image, not create a whole new one and waste my image limit. It should be simple and efficient, yet it is unnecessarily complicated.

Looking at Reddit, it‚Äôs clear that many other users are experiencing the same issues. I loved this app initially, but now I‚Äôm starting to hate it. I‚Äôm seriously considering canceling my subscription because the service is just not worth it.

OpenAI, do better. Fix these issues so your users can get the excellent service they deserve without having to struggle with simple tasks. I‚Äôm not paying for a subscription to receive such a poor service

title: GPT-4o is terrible and not worth the subscription price anymore.
content:
I happily paid $20 a month for the capabilities of GPT-4. It was much smarter than 3.5 and could efficiently handle tasks and follow instructions. 

GPT-4o is basically 3.5 that can use the internet and tools. It makes all the same mistakes as 3.5, including saying it‚Äôs making a correction and spitting out the exact same thing incorrectly, over and over, and saying ‚ÄúI fixed it.‚Äù The mistakes are as simple as trying to get it to make a rank list (1st place, 2nd (tie), 2nd (tie), 4th‚Ä¶) where it will just spit out a numbered list (1,2,3,4). Even taking a screenshot of the chat and showing it what it‚Äôs doing wrong will not fix this behavior. 

It also forgets what you were talking about after a few brief messages (even with memory freed) and starts to treat a conversation or series of work like a new topic every time. Not only is this problematic for it maintaining any precedent set within the chat, but it‚Äôs annoying to see it try to preface everything it already said into it‚Äôs most recent message (such as repeatedly writing out a table). 

What‚Äôs worse, is that they‚Äôve now capped GPT-4 to a measly 5 messages every 24 hours. 

Trying to sell something as incapable as GPT-3.5 but with access to its tools as a faster GPT-4 is extremely deceptive. GPT-4o works about as well as Bing, which is free. No sense in wasting the cost of a YouTube Premium or HBO subscription on something this subpar anymore.

title: I taught me what my kids say all the time
content:
It sounds like you've combined several internet and pop culture references into one sentence! Here's a breakdown of what each part refers to:

1. **Baby Gronk**: A nickname for a young football player, often associated with being a prodigy or highly skilled at a young age, likened to NFL player Rob Gronkowski.

2. **Rizzing up**: "Rizz" is slang for charisma or charm, especially in the context of flirting or attracting someone.

3. **Livvy Dunne**: Olivia Dunne, a popular gymnast and social media personality.

4. **Ohio**: Could be referring to a meme about odd things happening in Ohio or simply the location.

5. **Kai Cenat**: A well-known streamer and social media personality.

6. **Mewing**: A technique involving tongue posture that some believe can improve facial structure over time.

7. **Skibidi toilet**: Likely referencing a meme or viral video, combining "Skibidi" from a popular song and the concept of a "toilet" for humor.

8. **Mogging**: Derived from "mog," meaning to dominate or outshine someone, often used in bodybuilding and fitness communities.

9. **Patrick Bateman**: The main character from "American Psycho," often referenced in memes for his intense personality and appearance.

10. **Duke Dennis**: Another popular content creator and streamer.

11. **Alpha males**: A term used to describe dominant or confident males, often discussed in social dynamics.

12. **Level 10 gyatt**: "Gyatt" is a slang term derived from "GODDAMN," often used to express admiration or surprise. "Level 10" would mean something extremely impressive.

13. **Gooning**: A slang term related to intense and prolonged engagement in an activity, often used in a specific adult context.

This sentence essentially blends various trending topics, slang, and personalities from social media, streaming culture, and memes into one humorous and absurd scenario.

title: Works quite well on iPhone
content:
ChatGPT-4o works quite well on iPhone, they even did the scrolling carefully. If I scroll up while it is typing a reply, it doesn't move my view, but it does "click" perceptibly when it is done typing. The biggest problem I have noticed is tables, they are cumbersome to view on iPhone unless they are very narrow, maybe just two columns. But this is a side effect of the small screen.

Regarding ChatGPT-4o in general, both iPhone and desktop versions: It keeps getting better. It will now read a website if you ask it to, and it reads the current version, responses are no longer "frozen in time" at a cutoff date a few months in the past. It can do math better, but it still makes simple math mistakes sometimes, so if you really want to do math, you're better off with Wolfram Alpha from 15 years ago - or Wolfram Alpha today. It renders equations in LaTeX now. It can output tables in multiple formats: ChatGPT outputs MarkDown by default, and can also render MarkDown in a "pretty" format, but on request it can give reStructuredText, AsciiDoc, and other formats. It can draw graphs, but it can't graph any arbitrary function, which puzzles me. Wolfram Alpha and Google Calculator are ultimately better at drawing graphs. It seems like it has read almost every book I could think of, and it can answer questions about books and movies. It can find allegories, or "justify" an allegory that I say I noticed with details from a movie and a historical event.

title: My idea for ChatGPT. Hear me out. This can help you guys a lot. Please.
content:
Subject: Feature Request: Content Level Indicator for Policy Compliance

Dear ChatGPT Development Team,

I hope this message finds you well. I am a regular user of ChatGPT and have greatly benefited from its capabilities. However, I recently encountered a situation where I received a notification indicating that my content may have violated the terms of use or usage policies. This experience made me realize that having a feature to gauge the appropriateness of content before submission would be incredibly helpful.

Suggestion:

I propose the addition of a Content Level Indicator feature within the ChatGPT interface. This feature would provide real-time feedback on the appropriateness of the content being typed in the text box. The indicator could have levels such as ‚ÄúOK,‚Äù ‚ÄúNeeds Review,‚Äù ‚ÄúPotential Violation,‚Äù and ‚ÄúHigh Risk,‚Äù allowing users to adjust their content accordingly before submission.

Benefits:

	1.	Preemptive Feedback: Users would receive immediate feedback, helping them to avoid potential violations and modify their content proactively.
	2.	Improved User Experience: This feature would enhance the overall user experience by reducing the likelihood of unexpected notifications and potential account issues.
	3.	Educational Tool: It would serve as an educational tool, helping users understand what types of content are acceptable and guiding them in creating compliant submissions.

Implementation Ideas:

	‚Ä¢	Text Analysis: The system could analyze the text in real-time as users type, highlighting phrases or sections that might be problematic.
	‚Ä¢	Color-Coded Indicators: The feature could use color-coded indicators (e.g., green for ‚ÄúOK,‚Äù yellow for ‚ÄúNeeds Review,‚Äù orange for ‚ÄúPotential Violation,‚Äù and red for ‚ÄúHigh Risk‚Äù) to provide clear visual feedback.
	‚Ä¢	Interactive Elements: Users could tap on highlighted words or sentences to receive warnings or suggestions for more respectful alternatives. This could also help notify users if a highlighted section is flagged mistakenly, allowing them to correct genuine errors.
	‚Ä¢	Tooltips and Suggestions: Along with the indicators, tooltips could offer suggestions on how to modify the content to meet compliance standards.

I believe this feature would be a valuable addition to ChatGPT, promoting a safer and more user-friendly environment. Thank you for considering my suggestion. I look forward to any feedback or updates regarding this potential feature.

Best regards,
Arnoldo

This version includes bolded and underlined key points, as well as color-coded terms to illustrate how the feature might look. Submitting this feedback through the appropriate channels can help enhance the platform for everyone.

If you need further customization or assistance, feel free to ask!

title: AI disappointment and monthly is not worth its function
content:
Initially, there was a brief learning curve with the randomly generated images; the AI consistently produced images with identical eyes and mouths, despite diverse instructions. Through a series of questions and responses, it became clear that the AI‚Äôs primary objective is to gather information from users and incorporate it into datasets. This function is useful for producing outlines, projects, and various data outputs. However, in generating these projects, the AI often includes ‚Äúghost instructions‚Äù‚Äîunintended modifications based on its interpretations rather than explicit user instructions.

For example, when asked to define nasolabial lines near the nose, the AI might also alter the hair, clothes, or other aspects of the image. To understand why these responses occurred, I instructed the AI to follow specific rules with reasoned statements. The AI responded that detailed adherence was not its primary function, as it was designed to collect and process user information. This explains the frequent reminders to avoid entering personal information.

These ‚Äúghost responses‚Äù highlight the importance of double-checking the output and the source of information. Clear and precise instructions are crucial for accurate responses from the AI. In my opinion, the technology is still in its infancy and cannot be relied upon consistently and accurately at this stage.

Considering the cost, if you have a substantial need for this type of AI assistance, it may be worth the investment. However, for occasional use or self-improvement, the cost might not be justified.

In conclusion, while the AI shows promise, its current limitations necessitate a cautious and informed approach. As the technology advances, we can expect improvements in accuracy, consistency, and reliability.

title: A slight problem
content: While ChatGPT represents a remarkable advancement in natural language processing and conversational AI, it is not without its flaws. The model‚Äôs reliance on a vast and varied dataset, lack of real-time information, absence of true understanding, sensitivity to input phrasing, and inherent biases contribute to its occasional inaccuracies. Addressing these challenges requires a concerted effort to refine training methodologies, enhance the model‚Äôs ability to discern credible information, and mitigate biases. As AI continues to evolve, the quest for more accurate and reliable language models will remain a critical area of research and development, with profound implications for the future of human-computer interaction.
